domestic banks for those reporting requirements. It can do so because no other government wields control over such huge financial and consumer markets, and this power imbalance is at the heart of The Hypocritical Hegemon. The rest of the world, in particular the European Union, despite being frustrated about the redistributive impact of US hypocrisy, fears US retaliation against banks that depend on the American market and thus will likely not challenge US hegemony. In the end, the US now provides tax haven conditions at home, and it is the ordinary taxpayer who bears the brunt of this hypocritical policy. Hakelberg surveys what can be done to offset that burden.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBanks and banking, ForeignxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aConfidential communicationsxBankingzEuropean Union countries. 0aTax administration and procedurexInternational cooperation. 0aTax evasion (International law) 0aTax evasion (International law). 0aTax evasionzEuropean Union countries. 0aTax evasionzUnited States. 0aTaxationxPolitical aspectszEuropean Union countries. 0aTaxationxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aBusiness (General). 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aTaxation, tax avoidance, evasion, hegemony, international taxation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter